        <tr bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
          <td width="18%" valign="top"><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Quietman</b></font></td>
          <td>
            <font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><font size="1" color="#000080" face="Verdana, Arial">posted 08-05-98 06:44 PM CT (US)</font></font>
            <hr>
            <font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">For me at least, the novelty of these color variations has totally worn off. I won't spend another cent on these questionable color varations.</font>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Months ago, I was intrigued by the previous set of 4 holiday variations, so I bought the red snowman and the black skull. And I still think the black skull looks very cool.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">And then there were the neon psych eyes, and I actually bought one of those too. I don't think it looks cool -- it's the ugliest PEZ I ever saw. I bought it just in case it becomes valuable one day.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">But now, it seems like the floodgates have been opened, and these "special" offers are going to become EXTREMELY commonplace, effective immediately. They're just going to keep pumping out color variations, as long as there are collectors who keep shelling out $20+ a pop to get that coveted chartreuse snowman.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Forget it -- I'm out. I think they're going to keep releasing these color oddities as long as they can make lots of money (which means, they'll keep doing it for a while yet). By which point, everyone will be so sick of the color variations that NONE of them will be worth anything.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">So if you really like the way they look, and if you have $20 burning a hole in your pocket, don't let me stand in your way. But if you think these color variations will ever be worth anything, as collectibles, I bet you're wrong.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">And the thing is, how is ANYBODY supposed to know whether any given production run is really, truly limited to "3000" or whatever number the dealers claim? There's simply no way to validate those numbers. I'm spending my money on other things, thanks anyway.</font></p>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr bgcolor="#F7F7F7">
          <td width="18%" valign="top"><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Michael Porter</b></font></td>
          <td>
            <font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><font size="1" color="#000080" face="Verdana, Arial">posted 08-05-98 06:57 PM CT (US)</font></font>
            <hr>
            <font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">While I understand the price issue is a concern, I am MOST happy to have as many head color variations as they crank out! I *really* enjoy the way they display.</font>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Like I said, the $ issues are my only point concern. I would advise ANYBODY who is buying these as an investment to stop! Buy PEZ (or any collectible for that matter) because you like it, not for an investment!</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Quietman raises interesting points about length of run and depreciation, but if these are really important when making your decision to purchase these variations, well, as I said, don't buy 'em too.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">'Course, this is just me. I'm not the real expert. ~</font></p>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
          <td width="18%" valign="top"><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Quietman</b></font></td>
          <td>
            <font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><font size="1" color="#000080" face="Verdana, Arial">posted 08-06-98 08:25 AM CT (US)</font></font>
            <hr>
            <font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Re: Michael's advice to not buy PEZ "as an investment".... I think I know what he's saying, but I would phrase it differently: I'd say, don't buy PEZ *solely* as an investment.</font>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">I enjoy collecting PEZ, esp. the new issues that I can buy retail. But, when it comes to buying older PEZzes, I've sometimes paid over $50 apiece, like when I bought my Zorro dispenser. I simply couldn't justify spending $50+ on a PEZ dispenser if there wasn't some element of it being an "investment."</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">Not so much investment as in, "Oh boy, I'll get rich off of this!" More like, "Yeah, it's a lot of money for a little piece of plastic... but if I need the cash, I should be able to sell it for at least as much as I paid for it." So for me, it's both a hobby and an investment.</font></p>
            <p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">But I have to admit, the black skull looks much, much cooler than the regular skull. I'd love to buy a black witch to go with him... and I would buy it if it cost, say, $5.<br></font></p>
          </td>
        </tr>
